theorem Topology.interiorClosure_iter8_idempotent
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] (A : Set X) :
    interior (closure (interior (closure (interior (closure (interior
      (closure (interior (closure (interior (closure (interior
        (closure A)))))))))))) =
      interior (closure A) := by
  -- Use the 7-fold idempotence lemma to simplify the innermost part.
  have h₁ :=
    Topology.interiorClosure_iter7_idempotent (A := A)
  -- Apply one more `interior ∘ closure` to both sides of `h₁`.
  have h₂ :
      interior (closure
        (interior (closure (interior (closure (interior
          (closure (interior (closure (interior (closure (interior
            (closure A)))))))))))) =
        interior (closure (interior (closure A))) := by
    simpa using
      congrArg (fun S : Set X => interior (closure S)) h₁
  -- A final application of the basic idempotence lemma completes the proof.
  simpa [Topology.interiorClosure_idempotent (A := A)] using h₂

theorem interior_union_open_right
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A B : Set X} (hB : IsOpen B) :
    interior (A ∪ B : Set X) = interior A ∪ B := by
  classical
  ext x
  constructor
  · intro hx
    by_cases hxB : x ∈ B
    · exact Or.inr hxB
    · -- `x ∉ B`; we will show `x ∈ interior A`.
      rcases hx with ⟨U, hUopen, hxU, hUsub⟩
      -- Consider the open set `U \ B`.
      have hVopen : IsOpen (U \ B) := hUopen.diff hB
      have hxV : x ∈ U \ B := ⟨hxU, hxB⟩
      -- Points of `U \ B` cannot lie in `B`; hence they must lie in `A`.
      have hVsubA : (U \ B : Set X) ⊆ A := by
        intro y hy
        have h_yU : y ∈ U := hy.1
        have h_yNotB : y ∉ B := hy.2
        have hyUnion : y ∈ A ∪ B := hUsub h_yU
        cases hyUnion with
        | inl hA => exact hA
        | inr hBmem => exact False.elim (h_yNotB hBmem)
      exact Or.inl ⟨U \ B, hVopen, hxV, hVsubA⟩
  · intro hx
    cases hx with
    | inl hxIntA =>
        -- `interior A ⊆ interior (A ∪ B)` by monotonicity.
        exact (interior_mono
                (Set.subset_union_left : (A : Set X) ⊆ A ∪ B)) hxIntA
    | inr hxB =>
        -- Since `B` is open and contained in `A ∪ B`, it lies in the interior.
        have hBsubset : (B : Set X) ⊆ interior (A ∪ B) :=
          interior_maximal
            (by
              intro y hy
              exact Or.inr hy)
            hB
        exact hBsubset hxB

theorem Topology.isClosed_of_closureInterior_eq
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X}
    (h : closure (interior A) = (A : Set X)) :
    IsClosed (A : Set X) := by
  have hClosed : IsClosed (closure (interior A)) := isClosed_closure
  simpa [h] using hClosed
